[`json.Marshal()`][1] expects a single value, and [`time.Parse()`][2] returns 2 values: the parsed time and an error. You have to handle that yourself and not pass it to `json.Marshal()`, for example:

    func (ns *NullString) MarshalJSON() ([]byte, error) {
    	if !ns.Valid {
    		return []byte(&quot;null&quot;), nil
    	}
    	t, err := time.Parse(time.RFC3339, ns.String)
    	if err != nil {
    		return nil, err
    	}
    	return json.Marshal(t.Format(&quot;15:04:05&quot;))
    }

Testing it:

	ns := &amp;NullString{}
	data, err := json.Marshal(ns)
	fmt.Println(string(data), err)

	ns = &amp;NullString{
		NullString: sql.NullString{
			String: time.Time{}.Add(time.Minute * 1029).Format(time.RFC3339),
			Valid:  true,
		},
	}
	data, err = json.Marshal(ns)
	fmt.Println(string(data), err)

Output (try it on the [Go Playground][3]):

    null &lt;nil&gt;
    &quot;17:09:00&quot; &lt;nil&gt;

Also be careful with the receiver type. You used pointer receivers (`ns *NullString`), yet you use your `NullString` as non-pointers in the `LogItem` struct. Which means when marshaling values of your `LogItem`, this `NullString.MarshalJSON()` will not be called. So instead use non-pointer receiver.

    func (ns NullString) MarshalJSON() ([]byte, error) {
        // ...
    }

  [1]: https://golang.org/pkg/encoding/json/#Marshal
  [2]: https://golang.org/pkg/time/#Parse
  [3]: https://play.golang.org/p/-3nBSCgfWBG

